    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "This was a naive attitude at best — expressing a kind of “identity crisis” by early 20th century people. In effect they forced themselves to make a terrible decision, cutting themselves off from the past and its treasures — including the power of ornamentation. It was not understood until only recently that ornament, like biophilia, plays a key role in generating comfort and well-being in the built environment. Ornament employs the smallest articulated scales to generate organized complexity. We “feed visually” on this organized complexity, which makes it a necessary component of our environment, and not some aesthetic or philosophical ideal. This is why people all over the world and throughout history have consistently generated ornament.",
      "id": "23464134357445"
